03:50.689 --> 03:54.066
I did four stories
about extinction for

03:54.151 --> 03:55.234
National Geographic magazine.

03:58.655 --> 04:00.907
You go to these
beautiful landscapes.

04:03.201 --> 04:05.912
There's dinosaurs
from horizon to horizon.

04:10.834 --> 04:13.794
And you think,
"That was so far back then,

04:15.213 --> 04:19.007
"what if it's going on right now
and everybody's missing it?"

04:22.220 --> 04:25.556
Each year,
about one in a million species

04:25.641 --> 04:27.433
should expire naturally.

04:29.353 --> 04:30.937
In the next few decades,

04:31.271 --> 04:33.439
we'll be driving species
to extinction...

04:33.523 --> 04:36.067
...a thousand times faster
than they should be.

04:37.277 --> 04:38.778
It's difficult to estimate

04:38.862 --> 04:41.989
precisely how many species
we're gonna lose.

04:42.366 --> 04:44.116
In a hundred years or so,

04:44.493 --> 04:47.954
we could lose up to 50%
of all the species on Earth.

04:50.749 --> 04:52.041
I remember thinking,

04:52.125 --> 04:54.543
"This is the biggest story
in the world."

04:56.797 --> 04:58.631
It's like we're living
in the age of dinosaurs,

04:59.341 --> 05:01.258
but we can do something
about it.

05:24.783 --> 05:27.618
A friend of mine just
reported up in that area.

05:27.703 --> 05:28.995
Roger.

05:29.079 --> 05:31.163
The blue whale
is the biggest creature

05:31.248 --> 05:32.873
that ever lived on the planet.

05:32.958 --> 05:34.750
Bigger than any dinosaur ever.

05:36.336 --> 05:39.130
Just like dinosaurs,
they're going extinct.

05:39.673 --> 05:40.840
It's coming in hot!

05:40.924 --> 05:42.216
There it is!

05:43.635 --> 05:44.844
Look at him.

05:44.928 --> 05:46.262
Back in the days of whaling,

05:48.515 --> 05:50.016
they were hunted
to near-extinction,

05:50.392 --> 05:52.601
down to about two percent
of their population.

05:53.353 --> 05:55.896
Now they're getting decimated
by shipping traffic.

05:56.606 --> 05:57.648
Go for it.

05:58.358 --> 05:59.567
He's coming up to the right.

05:59.651 --> 06:00.693
To the right.

06:00.777 --> 06:02.903
My hope is that
if you can show people

06:02.988 --> 06:05.197
the beauty of these animals,

06:06.908 --> 06:08.367
there's a chance
to save these things.

06:26.803 --> 06:29.055
One of the cool things
about a blue whale

06:29.848 --> 06:32.725
is that it has the loudest song
in the animal kingdom,

06:33.310 --> 06:34.560
but you can't hear it,

06:35.645 --> 06:37.772
because it's below
our threshold for hearing.

06:42.360 --> 06:44.779
We look out at the world through
these eyes and these ears,

06:44.863 --> 06:46.280
and you think, "Oh, that's it.

06:47.199 --> 06:48.949
"That's everything
that there is to see."

06:52.662 --> 06:55.247
But there's this hidden world
on almost every level.

06:58.835 --> 07:00.711
What I want to do is
get people to see it.

07:27.447 --> 07:28.989
We get off the boat,

07:29.616 --> 07:32.535
and this fisherman comes up
to our interpreter

07:32.619 --> 07:34.829
and says, "Can you give me $500?

07:34.913 --> 07:37.289
"I found this buoy.
There's a $500 reward.

07:37.374 --> 07:39.583
"lt needs to be returned
up to America."

07:42.212 --> 07:43.337
And I said, "Just a minute.

07:43.421 --> 07:44.463
"Let me take a look
at this buoy."

07:45.882 --> 07:47.967
And I look at it, and it says,

07:48.051 --> 07:50.928
"Return to Chris Clark,
Cornell Bioacoustic laboratory."

07:51.012 --> 07:52.138
I said, "I know this guy."

07:58.937 --> 08:01.981
Chris had been pioneering
new ways to record whales

08:02.065 --> 08:03.107
for 30 years.

08:04.317 --> 08:06.402
He basically proved
that these animals

08:06.486 --> 08:08.320
could hear themselves
across oceans.

08:10.407 --> 08:12.575
And so, to me,
finding that buoy

08:12.659 --> 08:14.076
was like finding a message
in a bottle.

08:17.414 --> 08:19.790
We built these
recording systems.

08:20.792 --> 08:24.295
We dropped them in the ocean,
and they record continuously.

08:25.714 --> 08:29.675
Whales and dolphins
and anything that's out there...

08:29.759 --> 08:31.051
we try and record.

08:33.597 --> 08:35.014
So, the first time,

08:35.472 --> 08:38.976
I knew there was a blue whale
singing nearby.

08:39.436 --> 08:43.438
l could see it on the display,
but I couldn't hear it.

08:45.233 --> 08:48.194
So what do you have to do?
You have to speed it up.

08:51.990 --> 08:54.158
And still, the hair goes up
on the back of my neck,

08:54.367 --> 08:55.618
and it just, like-- It's like,

08:56.286 --> 08:58.329
"Damn! That's fabulous."

09:05.420 --> 09:07.379
As we listen more and more

09:07.464 --> 09:09.256
around different parts
of the planet,

09:11.760 --> 09:15.429
whether it's frozen Arctic ocean

09:15.889 --> 09:19.808
or the deepest jungles
of Central Africa,

09:20.560 --> 09:22.228
the whole world is singing.

09:24.481 --> 09:27.066
Clicking and grinding
and whistling and thumping.

09:29.069 --> 09:30.653
But we've stopped listening.

09:38.578 --> 09:40.746
The Cornell Bioacoustical Laboratory

09:40.830 --> 09:44.208
has the largest repository
of animal sounds on the planet.

09:46.127 --> 09:48.295
They've been collecting them
since the 1 930s.

09:49.923 --> 09:51.548
You can think of it as a museum,

09:51.633 --> 09:53.759
just like there could be
bird skins or, you know,

09:53.843 --> 09:55.135
beetles tacked up on a wall.

09:57.138 --> 09:59.515
So there's this range of sounds

09:59.683 --> 10:02.643
from the largest animal
ever to live on this planet

10:03.770 --> 10:05.813
to the tiniest, little insects.

10:10.068 --> 10:11.735
This is a song recording

10:12.487 --> 10:15.364
of a male 'o'o singing
on Kaua'i.

10:18.076 --> 10:19.702
These birds mate for life,

10:20.328 --> 10:22.288
so he would be singing
a duet with his mate,

10:22.372 --> 10:25.082
where he sings, and then
she sings back and forth.

10:27.711 --> 10:29.378
Here comes the male's song.

10:30.005 --> 10:31.213
There's no response.

10:32.882 --> 10:35.050
Here's the male's song again.

10:37.012 --> 10:39.346
That's the last male of a species,

10:39.889 --> 10:41.473
singing for a female

10:42.475 --> 10:43.475
who will never come.

10:46.229 --> 10:48.314
He is totally alone.

10:51.318 --> 10:53.027
And now his voice is gone.

10:56.823 --> 10:58.907
In the brief lifetime
of this collection,

10:59.951 --> 11:01.076
70 years or so,

11:02.078 --> 11:05.748
many of the species that
were recorded are now extinct.

11:07.667 --> 11:11.003
So the repository
is a living example

11:11.087 --> 11:14.882
of the massive rate
of extinction that's happening.

11:26.144 --> 11:28.771
There's been five major extinctions
in the history of the planet.

11:30.148 --> 11:31.357
There's the Ordovician,

11:33.151 --> 11:34.234
the Devonian,

11:35.987 --> 11:37.237
the Permian...

11:38.990 --> 11:40.574
...there was the triassic-jurassic,

11:41.910 --> 11:43.452
...and then the K-t extinction,

11:44.245 --> 11:45.996
...the one that killed
the dinosaurs.

11:47.999 --> 11:51.210
It's very difficult
to comprehend deep time.

11:51.920 --> 11:54.630
You know, 4.6 billion years
of Earth's history.

11:56.216 --> 11:58.217
But if you take, say,
the history of the Earth

11:58.385 --> 12:00.761
and try to squeeze it into
a 24-hour clock,

12:02.305 --> 12:03.639
where does man fit
on that clock?

12:05.392 --> 12:07.976
A few seconds before midnight.
That's it.

12:09.187 --> 12:10.979
We're the new kid on the block.

12:12.190 --> 12:13.524
What we're seeing now...

12:14.692 --> 12:16.068
...is called the anthropocene,
the new epoch.

12:18.154 --> 12:20.155
Anthropocene means
the time of humans.

12:21.825 --> 12:25.661
It's when the impact of humans
is leaving itself as a mark

12:25.745 --> 12:27.538
in the fossil record
of the future.

12:30.208 --> 12:31.917
65 million years ago,

12:32.419 --> 12:34.837
there was an asteroid
that struck

12:34.921 --> 12:36.672
and caused the dinosaurs
to go extinct.

12:38.633 --> 12:40.509
When it comes to
the sixth extinction event,

12:40.969 --> 12:45.055
we have no problem
identifying the cause.

12:47.100 --> 12:49.101
Humanity has become the asteroid.

12:53.815 --> 12:55.524
We're on that tipping point now,

12:56.025 --> 12:57.734
where it's either...

12:58.778 --> 13:01.655
too late or just the beginning
of a movement.

13:02.699 --> 13:05.576
So, there's two pieces
of whale and one piece of horse.

13:05.660 --> 13:06.994
At the Hump restaurant,

13:07.662 --> 13:09.455
