And I thought,
"Well, if we could prove

13:28.141 --> 13:29.808
"that endangered whales
are being served right here,

13:29.893 --> 13:31.602
"on the shores of America,

13:31.978 --> 13:33.395
"we would stop
that conversation."

13:33.688 --> 13:35.772
Stop the murder!
Stop the death!

13:35.857 --> 13:38.275
Hump restaurant is to blame!

13:39.319 --> 13:40.986
The animal-rights community
took it up,

13:41.070 --> 13:42.613
but the restaurant
didn't close down.

13:46.075 --> 13:48.076
There's this one guy
I'd never heard of before,

13:48.953 --> 13:50.204
his name is Ady Gil.

13:51.414 --> 13:54.166
He took some gear and put it out
in front of the Hump restaurant,

13:54.459 --> 13:55.459
as people are going in.

13:55.919 --> 13:57.294
So, what are you doing?

13:57.378 --> 13:58.462
I'm protesting.

13:59.005 --> 14:02.841
Yesterday, there were like
200 people here, protesting,

14:02.926 --> 14:04.510
and l thought, you know,

14:04.594 --> 14:06.637
somebody needs to keep
the pressure on.

14:07.055 --> 14:09.389
If you look at the Academy
Awards and the Golden Globes,

14:09.474 --> 14:12.017
those are his screens,
and that's all his projections.

14:13.770 --> 14:16.271
And, so, he parks this Ferrari
right next to the van,

14:16.564 --> 14:18.899
and the owner comes out
and tells Ady, he says,

14:19.275 --> 14:20.734
"How long
are you gonna be doing this?"

14:21.069 --> 14:23.403
And he thought that
I was just some hippie, you know,

14:23.488 --> 14:24.780
gonna be here for
a day or two.

14:24.864 --> 14:26.156
I said, "Listen, man.

14:26.241 --> 14:28.575
"I can be here for a month or two
or a year or whatever.

14:28.952 --> 14:31.787
"How long can you survive
while I am here?"

14:32.705 --> 14:34.581
Ten days later,
the restaurant closes down.

14:36.584 --> 14:38.502
To me,
it was a beautiful moment.

14:38.878 --> 14:40.254
Everybody had gone home,

14:40.588 --> 14:42.673
and this one guy with
this big, bright light,

14:43.007 --> 14:45.467
and keeps the light shining
on this subject.

14:46.761 --> 14:49.638
Shut it down!

14:55.562 --> 14:58.605
There are thousands of people
all over the world,

14:59.816 --> 15:03.944
willing and able and changing
their careers to save species.

15:08.575 --> 15:11.034
They go to some of
the darkest, grimmest,

15:11.119 --> 15:13.287
most unsafe places
on the planet.

15:13.454 --> 15:15.455
Let's save the shark!
Let's save the shark!

15:15.540 --> 15:17.916
Over 800 environmental activists
have been killed

15:18.167 --> 15:19.418
in just the last decade.

15:20.712 --> 15:22.379
So these guys are doing
the tough work,

15:23.256 --> 15:25.173
and we never hear about them.
They're not household names.

15:27.010 --> 15:29.636
Shawn Heinrichs,
I live in Boulder, Colorado.

15:29.762 --> 15:31.888
You can't get any more
landlocked than Colorado.

15:32.932 --> 15:35.309
And I found out that there's
this incredible ocean activist

15:36.728 --> 15:38.061
living right down the street

15:38.896 --> 15:41.398
who quit his job as a CFO
for a tech company

15:41.858 --> 15:43.567
so he could help save
endangered species.

15:45.320 --> 15:47.821
Shawn's doing some of the best,
most groundbreaking work

15:47.989 --> 15:50.407
that I've seen anywhere
in the world.

15:52.285 --> 15:56.413
Isla Mujeres was
the largest shark-fishing island

15:56.789 --> 15:58.457
on the east coast of Mexico.

15:59.167 --> 16:01.251
At least 20,
if not more, long-liners...

16:01.336 --> 16:03.462
...were targeting sharks
each and every single day.

16:04.297 --> 16:05.631
Shawn helped turn
this hunting ground...

16:06.382 --> 16:08.216
...into one of the top places
in the world

16:08.301 --> 16:09.718
where you can actually
go and watch sharks.

16:11.638 --> 16:13.889
Now you have this
community of ex-shark fishermen

16:14.307 --> 16:16.516
who are making much more money
taking tourists out

16:16.643 --> 16:18.185
to swim with whale sharks

16:18.269 --> 16:19.895
than killing sharks on long-lines.

16:21.689 --> 16:22.814
It's just simple economics.

16:26.694 --> 16:29.237
Shawn often works
with his buddy, Paul Hilton,

16:29.447 --> 16:30.781
an investigative photojournalist.

16:31.366 --> 16:34.242
They can't help but to get themselves
into dangerous situations.

16:34.369 --> 16:35.369
Traveler's paradise.

16:35.828 --> 16:36.995
Paul's a photojournalist,

16:37.538 --> 16:39.706
like me,
focused on endangered species.

16:41.125 --> 16:42.417
He's brilliant at what he does.

16:44.796 --> 16:49.007
Paul and Shawn try to bust rings
selling endangered species.

16:49.717 --> 16:52.010
We're gonna blow the lid
off this place, right?

16:52.095 --> 16:54.971
Shawn's pretty full-on.
I love his enthusiasm.

16:55.056 --> 16:57.391
He talks far too much
when we're on assignment.

16:57.475 --> 16:58.725
There's always that issue

16:58.810 --> 17:00.477
of me having to go to him
and say, "mate, wind it up."

17:00.561 --> 17:01.728
I think it's
the American in him.

17:02.063 --> 17:03.980
l'm rolling. l can distract.

17:06.233 --> 17:07.818
And a lot of the situations
we go into,

17:07.902 --> 17:09.319
it's always nice
to go in as teams,

17:09.404 --> 17:10.779
because you're going
into situations where

17:11.446 --> 17:13.281
you get caught up
in the moment with the camera,

17:13.449 --> 17:14.866
and you'll actually
photograph it, and

17:15.076 --> 17:16.535
there's no one
watching your back.

17:16.618 --> 17:18.078
Ask for the toilet.
Where's the toilet?

17:18.162 --> 17:19.621
Paul and Shawn
have this technique

17:19.705 --> 17:21.707
of... They have a camera
sitting around their neck,

17:21.790 --> 17:23.666
and most people think you
have to put it up to your eye

17:23.751 --> 17:25.377
to look through it and to shoot.

17:25.461 --> 17:27.002
And it's actually a video camera,

17:27.088 --> 17:28.755
and it's rolling the whole time.

17:28.840 --> 17:29.923
So many.

17:31.259 --> 17:35.345
And this is the Jaws,
movie Jaws?

17:36.806 --> 17:38.140
Don't push it too much, Shawn.

17:38.224 --> 17:39.766
Okay, cool. Very cool.

17:39.851 --> 17:41.935
I don't know about you. That's the
most fins I've ever, ever seen.

17:42.019 --> 17:43.186
How did you find out
about this?

17:43.271 --> 17:44.312
Facebook, basically.

17:44.564 --> 17:45.689
I mean, colleagues, mates...

17:46.399 --> 17:48.275
We just walked straight in, basically.

17:48.359 --> 17:49.359
Wow.

17:50.278 --> 17:51.570
How long were you there?

17:51.654 --> 17:52.779
Ten, 1 5 minutes.

