You did all this
in ten, 1 5 minutes?

17:54.949 --> 17:55.949
Oh, yeah, mate.

17:56.868 --> 17:58.452
Yeah.

17:58.703 --> 17:59.703
Are we almost there, Paul?

17:59.787 --> 18:01.163
Yeah, so, it's the next block.

18:02.206 --> 18:03.707
I didn't think that
the illegal-wildlife trade

18:03.791 --> 18:05.459
would be so overt.

18:08.921 --> 18:10.672
You can go down streets,

18:11.424 --> 18:14.176
and every other shop will be
full of endangered creatures.

18:14.469 --> 18:15.635
Look at this one right here.

18:15.928 --> 18:17.679
It's not just shark fins.

18:18.306 --> 18:20.056
It's just about
everything endangered

18:20.141 --> 18:21.850
in the world is for sale there.

18:25.605 --> 18:27.564
With the explosion
of demand in China

18:27.648 --> 18:28.648
for shark-fin soup,

18:29.358 --> 18:31.735
it was estimated
that 250,000 sharks

18:31.861 --> 18:34.821
are caught for the fin trade
every single day.

18:36.824 --> 18:38.283
Probably no other species

18:38.367 --> 18:40.327
illustrates what's going on in
the oceans right now

18:40.411 --> 18:41.578
better than sharks.

18:42.163 --> 18:44.539
Sharks predate dinosaurs.

18:44.874 --> 18:47.501
They survived four
mass-extinction events.

18:49.587 --> 18:52.964
And just this one generation
that I've been alive,

18:53.382 --> 18:55.967
we've cut down their ranks
about 90%.

18:59.472 --> 19:01.932
I was following
a group of shark finners

19:02.016 --> 19:03.934
in Indonesia, and they were
moving around camp to camp.

19:06.354 --> 19:07.354
And, then, one morning,

19:07.897 --> 19:09.981
I saw something reflecting
off in the coral reef

19:10.066 --> 19:11.191
in the shallow water.

19:13.277 --> 19:14.986
And what I discovered
was just horrific.

