There's this beautiful
tawny nurse shark,

19:20.868 --> 19:22.244
but it had all its fins cut off.

19:24.080 --> 19:25.997
And it was trying to swim,
but it couldn't swim.

19:26.082 --> 19:28.667
And it was heartbreaking,

19:28.751 --> 19:30.752
'cause it's like... This is
what the reality is.

19:30.837 --> 19:32.921
This is the thing that nobody gets.

19:49.272 --> 19:51.523
Now, are we gonna get... Any
luck with us getting in there?

19:53.526 --> 19:54.776
Okay.

19:54.861 --> 19:56.111
Shawn has an interpreter.

19:58.698 --> 19:59.948
I don't want to say her name,

20:00.032 --> 20:02.409
but she's been doing
undercover work in China

20:02.493 --> 20:04.119
for several decades.

20:05.371 --> 20:07.497
The first place she took us
was a place

20:07.582 --> 20:09.374
that they couldn't ever
get into before.

20:11.043 --> 20:13.628
Basically, the Walmart
of the endangered-species trade

20:13.713 --> 20:14.713
in Hong Kong.

20:18.259 --> 20:19.426
Over the years,

20:19.802 --> 20:21.803
I've actually worked really hard
to get into this facility.

20:22.597 --> 20:24.180
So has Paul
and so has his friends.

20:24.265 --> 20:27.434
And we've managed to maybe
step in the door for 30 seconds.

20:27.518 --> 20:28.560
Hey!

20:28.644 --> 20:29.728
What's wrong?

20:33.733 --> 20:35.942
His staff would come out
and push us away,

20:36.235 --> 20:37.986
threaten to call the police.

20:38.070 --> 20:40.155
Hands, machete,

20:40.448 --> 20:42.240
kicked out the door,
"don't ever come back."

20:46.203 --> 20:47.370
Here's what we'll do.

20:47.455 --> 20:49.080
We have a car waiting
with all the stuff in it.

20:49.832 --> 20:52.042
I brought along a couple of
colleagues from the Hump bust.

20:52.835 --> 20:54.711
Heather Rally, who does
undercover work for us.

20:55.504 --> 20:56.504
And Charles Hambleton,

20:56.589 --> 20:59.215
who's sort of my director
of covert operations.

20:59.300 --> 21:01.259
In the alley here,
on the right-hand side?

21:01.344 --> 21:02.928
We invented a cover.

21:03.346 --> 21:05.388
We pretended like we were
on a culinary tour

21:05.556 --> 21:07.849
and we were looking for
exotic product.

21:07.975 --> 21:09.017
I think we stick to plan.

21:09.101 --> 21:11.269
We're going as culinary tourist
interests of Mr. Sawyer,

21:11.354 --> 21:13.730
and we're all here, learning
and taking pictures of culinary.

21:13.814 --> 21:15.482
You can get into
about as much trouble

21:15.566 --> 21:16.816
as you can possibly get into

21:16.901 --> 21:18.860
with a buttonhole camera
in China.

21:18.945 --> 21:20.028
If for some reason,

21:20.112 --> 21:21.655
we run into people
with badges and uniforms,

21:21.739 --> 21:23.782
strip off all the shit.

21:23.866 --> 21:25.825
Just rip it out from under your
shirt and throw it over a wall.

21:25.910 --> 21:27.994
Go right in.
Go in, go in, go in.

21:28.079 --> 21:29.329
Hi.

21:50.559 --> 21:52.644
We're starting a business
where we want to sell seafood.

21:53.187 --> 21:54.980
We have a seafood shop.

21:55.189 --> 21:57.190
Well, back where we do it,

21:57.274 --> 22:00.944
it's mainly tuna and marlin
and swordfish.

22:01.028 --> 22:03.029
They want to see something
more exciting.

22:03.406 --> 22:06.491
'Cause the Chinese traveler
and the Asian traveler

22:06.575 --> 22:08.743
has become big business now.
It's more than 50%.

22:10.329 --> 22:11.788
We should go.
We should probably go.

22:11.872 --> 22:12.914
No, no, no.

22:20.172 --> 22:22.465
-This is nice.
-Yeah.

22:26.137 --> 22:27.637
I need to go to
the bathroom bad.

22:27.722 --> 22:28.888
There's the bathroom.

22:28.973 --> 22:30.724
Oh, thank you, thank you.

23:08.679 --> 23:09.763
Yeah.

23:12.099 --> 23:13.475
Are these expensive, also?

23:19.523 --> 23:21.983
$44,800 US Dollar per kilo.

23:24.153 --> 23:25.695
No way.

23:35.581 --> 23:37.248
We ended up going down the road

23:37.333 --> 23:39.084
to another warehouse
on the Hong Kong waterfront.

23:39.168 --> 23:40.960
Louie, look at this.

23:41.045 --> 23:44.756
It must have been
1 0,000-20,000 fins in one location.

23:45.758 --> 23:47.967
This was one of the biggest
facilities on the planet.

23:48.135 --> 23:49.219
Look at that.
It looks like a blue.

23:49.303 --> 23:52.180
The scale of it was
just out of control.

23:52.264 --> 23:53.932
l've never seen anything like
that before in my life.

23:55.017 --> 23:56.184
Jesus!

24:04.068 --> 24:08.321
I feel like this world
is absolutely insane.

24:40.479 --> 24:42.313
I remember once diving

24:42.398 --> 24:43.982
the northernmost islands
of the Galapagos,

24:44.608 --> 24:47.318
Darwin lsland and Wolf Island.
You know, islands that

24:47.403 --> 24:49.320
Darwin actually never had
been to before.

24:53.450 --> 24:54.742
It's the land before time.

24:54.827 --> 24:57.871
I mean, it's like land
before humans got there.

25:03.752 --> 25:07.213
And I remember
this giant whale shark came by,

25:07.298 --> 25:09.174
and then a pod of dolphins came by.

25:09.967 --> 25:11.467
You know, this is back
when you shot film.

25:13.971 --> 25:16.514
And the whole frame was just
filled with wildlife.

25:18.851 --> 25:21.936
And this dolphin came
swimming from behind

25:22.146 --> 25:24.772
the front of the whale shark,
and it grabbed this tuna,

25:24.899 --> 25:27.650
and it brought it and looked
right at me and shook it,

25:27.943 --> 25:30.820
and it swallowed it, tail first
down its throat.

25:30.905 --> 25:32.322
And I thought, "You know,

25:32.656 --> 25:36.367
"this is when you want 37 pictures
on a 36 roll of film."

25:39.455 --> 25:41.581
It's just magical, absolutely magical.

25:48.714 --> 25:50.548
As underwater photographers,

25:52.051 --> 25:53.343
photojournalists really,

25:54.386 --> 25:58.389
we're documenting a time and a place

25:59.808 --> 26:02.727
that in the future
may not be there.

26:04.647 --> 26:06.189
And the clock is moving.

26:07.858 --> 26:09.275
The first photographs I shot...

26:09.360 --> 26:12.403
...the assignment for
National Geographic, 1960,

26:12.655 --> 26:13.863
I took a total of.. .

26:14.323 --> 26:17.784
...seven or eight frames on
two and a quarter square film,

26:18.202 --> 26:21.162
on ektachrome film,
and butted them together.

26:22.122 --> 26:25.792
It was the first underwater, color
panoramicever done on the reefs.

26:27.878 --> 26:30.046
And this was when I came back
in 1 989.

26:30.756 --> 26:33.174
The beautiful Barrier Reef
forest went to hell.

26:39.306 --> 26:41.224
Now I'm looking around
and saying, "Well,

26:41.850 --> 26:42.892
"what happened here?

26:45.062 --> 26:48.523
"It's not so far off from what
happened 65 million years ago."

26:50.276 --> 26:52.235
Extinction is often being driven by...

26:52.319 --> 26:53.444
...direct human activity,

26:53.529 --> 26:56.990
things like habitat destruction
or overfishing.

26:58.742 --> 27:00.576
And then there's
global climate change,

27:00.703 --> 27:02.078
which is happening
in a different way.

27:04.248 --> 27:05.915
So we have these
sort of dual things,

27:06.000 --> 27:07.667
like the direct hand of man,

27:08.836 --> 27:11.045
and the indirect hand of man
in the change of climate.

27:13.632 --> 27:15.675
Climate is controlled
by the oceans.

27:15.759 --> 27:17.844
The oceans are the big guy.
They're in control.

27:20.097 --> 27:22.640
And the oceans now
are slowly changing.

27:24.435 --> 27:26.853
And that is the danger
we face today.

27:27.438 --> 27:31.024
A mass extinction is driven
by a change of the environment...

27:31.317 --> 27:34.402
...and we are changing
the environment precisely

27:34.528 --> 27:37.363
along the lines
that can trigger off

27:37.489 --> 27:38.781
one of these great catastrophes.

27:42.161 --> 27:44.120
There's been
five mass extinctions,

27:44.496 --> 27:46.122
and they've had
different causes,

27:46.540 --> 27:50.293
but there's been
one common factor in all.. .

27:52.629 --> 27:55.590
a massive increase
in carbon dioxide.

27:57.343 --> 27:59.552
And we've never had
a carbon-dioxide spike

27:59.636 --> 28:00.928
like what's happening now.

28:03.349 --> 28:06.684
We are burning through
the fossil fuels laid down

28:06.769 --> 28:08.728
over hundreds of millions
of years.

28:09.313 --> 28:12.565
Really reversing
geological history, basically.

28:12.649 --> 28:14.317
And we're doing it
really, really fast.

28:20.324 --> 28:22.283
In the Gulf oil spill,

28:22.618 --> 28:25.620
about 4.9 million barrels of oil
were spilled.

28:27.664 --> 28:29.207
That represents about a quarter...

28:29.291 --> 28:31.501
...of what we use every single day
in the U.S.

28:33.712 --> 28:35.129
You look at an event

28:35.297 --> 28:36.589
like the Gulf oil spill,
and you think,

28:36.715 --> 28:38.841
"This is the biggest
environmental catastrophe

28:38.967 --> 28:40.218
"in America ever."

28:40.719 --> 28:44.389
But that spill is nothing
compared to the damage

28:44.473 --> 28:46.599
caused by us doing
everyday things

28:46.683 --> 28:48.059
we don't even think about.

28:50.104 --> 28:52.063
And I'm more guilty than anyone.

28:53.399 --> 28:55.066
The worst thing you can do
to the environment

28:55.150 --> 28:56.192
is make a film about it.

28:56.276 --> 28:57.360
This looks really cool.

28:57.528 --> 28:58.820
We did a carbon assessment

28:58.904 --> 29:00.029
of the first two years
of production.

29:01.156 --> 29:07.537
And I was horrified at how much
energy it takes to do what I do.

29:08.247 --> 29:09.539
Sweet. We're gonna
turn this one on.

29:10.124 --> 29:11.833
We're at the point where
we're making our lives

29:12.167 --> 29:14.127
a lot better for us,

29:15.462 --> 29:17.296
but we're doing it
at the expense of

29:17.381 --> 29:18.381
of everything going forward.

29:22.803 --> 29:24.720
We have many, many ways
to fix this problem.

29:26.014 --> 29:28.724
The question is,
are we gonna do it fast enough?

29:32.062 --> 29:33.229
What we know at the moment

29:33.313 --> 29:35.273
is we're driving this
out of control...

29:35.399 --> 29:38.484
...and the ocean's chemistry
is changing really rapidly.

29:38.569 --> 29:39.735
Scarily fast.

29:41.572 --> 29:44.031
When we put carbon dioxide
into the atmosphere,

29:44.408 --> 29:45.658
it doesn't all stay there.

29:46.994 --> 29:50.121
Between a third and a half
gets absorbed by the oceans.

29:51.957 --> 29:53.958
The CO2 reacts with water

29:54.168 --> 29:55.877
to form something
called carbonic acid,

29:57.129 --> 29:59.213
and each year, the ocean
becomes more and more acidic.

30:00.924 --> 30:03.134
If you want to know
what that does,

30:03.719 --> 30:06.262
get a seashell and drop it in,

30:06.513 --> 30:08.264
...you know, a glass of vinegar.

30:12.978 --> 30:17.607
A whole variety of creatures
will simply

30:17.691 --> 30:21.486
dissolve into the acid ocean
that we have created.

30:26.450 --> 30:28.659
There's massive death
in the oceans.

30:30.287 --> 30:31.829
It's already started.

30:32.456 --> 30:34.582
Well, it's not only started,
it's well underway.

30:36.460 --> 30:37.752
Those are larvae?

30:37.836 --> 30:39.629
Yeah.
See the little...

30:39.713 --> 30:41.130
The brown smudge?

30:41.215 --> 30:42.381
Yeah, yeah.

30:43.383 --> 30:46.594
Each year, we harvest
seven to ten billion oyster larvae...

30:46.678 --> 30:50.056
...that we send out to growers
throughout the Pacific northwest.

30:51.266 --> 30:54.477
I still remember the day
all of the larvae essentially

30:54.561 --> 30:56.646
in our entire hatchery
were on the bottom of the tanks.

30:57.439 --> 31:00.316
So around six billion larvae all died
in a single day.

31:04.947 --> 31:06.572
That deep-ocean water

31:06.657 --> 31:09.158
off the coast of Washington
and Oregon

31:09.451 --> 31:11.619
comes into
the hatchery intakes,

31:12.704 --> 31:14.580
...and they can't grow
their shell.

31:14.665 --> 31:16.249
lt's dissolving faster
than they can grow it.

31:19.002 --> 31:21.504
It seemed outlandish to think
that the ocean

31:21.880 --> 31:24.549
could be acidified enough to
cause these kinds of problems.

31:24.633 --> 31:26.801
It just seemed like something
from the distant future

31:26.885 --> 31:29.136
and nothing we ever had
to pay attention to.

31:31.807 --> 31:33.975
The rate of change
that we're seeing in the ocean

31:34.101 --> 31:37.436
and the change that it's gonna
create in our food chain...

31:37.938 --> 31:41.023
it's gonna be dramatic, and it's
gonna be in our lifetimes.

31:42.651 --> 31:44.026
The things
that we're used to eating

31:44.194 --> 31:46.028
may not be available anymore,

31:46.113 --> 31:47.780
and we may need to transition
to, you know,

31:47.864 --> 31:49.740
eating jellyfish
or something like that.

31:50.492 --> 31:51.784
Start a new trend.

31:58.500 --> 31:59.917
It sounds a bit silly,

32:00.002 --> 32:03.296
"Change your diet
and save the planet"

32:03.922 --> 32:07.925
But if humans could
become vegetarians now,

32:08.010 --> 32:09.719
you would make
a massive difference.

32:10.846 --> 32:12.430
By far and away,

32:12.514 --> 32:16.309
the biggest factor in terms
of this mass extinction

32:16.602 --> 32:19.937
is destroying natural habitat
or converting natural habitat

32:20.022 --> 32:21.355
into land for food.

32:23.233 --> 32:25.735
The more dependent we are
on meat, milk, and eggs,

32:26.320 --> 32:28.988
the greater the CO2
and methane emissions.

32:31.908 --> 32:34.910
Cattle and Brahmanas of all kind

32:35.954 --> 32:41.417
produce methane as a byproduct
of breaking down grass

32:41.627 --> 32:43.878
and other things that they feed on.

32:48.425 --> 32:49.884
So, the contractions

32:49.968 --> 32:52.511
are pushing this gas
out from the stomach,

32:53.764 --> 32:55.640
going through here and the
one-way valve and into that?

32:55.724 --> 32:57.516
Yes. And after this,
we collect inside the bag.

32:57.976 --> 32:59.769
So, how long has that bag
been collecting gas?

32:59.853 --> 33:01.145
Only two hours.

33:02.189 --> 33:05.816
Methane is something
like 22 times more potent

33:06.943 --> 33:09.487
as a climate-changing gas
than is CO2,

33:09.571 --> 33:11.947
so it doesn't take very much
methane to make a difference.

33:13.825 --> 33:17.203
A cow can basically
fill up a 55-gallon garbage bag

33:17.287 --> 33:19.288
full of methane every day.

33:21.416 --> 33:24.627
One cow's not a problem, but now
we have 1 .5 billion of them.

33:26.046 --> 33:28.381
And it's an incredibly
inefficient way of producing food.

33:31.927 --> 33:35.179
Three-quarters of agricultural land
is used just to feed livestock.

33:36.014 --> 33:37.390
When you factor in everything,

33:38.100 --> 33:40.601
the clearing of the land
for grazing, feeding,

33:40.686 --> 33:43.979
and transporting, livestock
causes more greenhouse gases

33:44.398 --> 33:47.692
than all the direct emissions
from the entire transportation sector.

33:49.611 --> 33:51.862
I don't think it's
a competition between these problems.

33:51.947 --> 33:53.781
l don't think one could
be put above the other.

33:53.865 --> 33:55.366
lt's like saying,
"well, is global warming

33:55.450 --> 33:58.119
worse than ocean acidification?"

33:58.453 --> 34:02.164
Or, "Is fishing all the big fish in
the sea worse than polluting it?"

34:02.791 --> 34:04.875
I think it'd be foolish
to try and single out

34:04.960 --> 34:07.086
any one of them to say
this is how we're gonna

34:07.170 --> 34:08.545
fix the planet's problems.

34:08.672 --> 34:10.505
We need to fight them
on all fronts.

34:22.728 --> 34:24.228
Look at all the rodents.

34:26.481 --> 34:28.149
They're like house cats.

34:30.610 --> 34:33.821
Look at this one.
lt's still alive.

34:36.158 --> 34:37.616
A lot of doors closing.

34:37.701 --> 34:38.743
Lights going off.

34:40.245 --> 34:41.536
That's scary, man.

34:41.621 --> 34:43.371
Yeah, we're definitely
not welcome here.

34:43.456 --> 34:46.500
In 2003, the government clamped
down on the wildlife markets

34:46.585 --> 34:49.879
across southern China, so things
started to go underground,

34:49.963 --> 34:52.047
so operating
in early hours of the morning.

34:52.966 --> 34:54.132
And it's horrific.

34:55.135 --> 34:56.260
They're shutting down.

34:56.762 --> 34:58.387
-What?
-They're shutting down.

34:58.472 --> 34:59.597
That's crazy.

34:59.681 --> 35:01.140
They're hiding them now.

35:02.392 --> 35:04.435
Oh, my gosh!

35:06.438 --> 35:10.024
This is a market that had to
switch places twice that year.

35:10.192 --> 35:11.567
Oh. What are they doing?

35:11.985 --> 35:13.569
I mean, they know they're
not supposed to be doing

35:13.653 --> 35:14.779
what they're doing.

35:16.782 --> 35:17.990
That's hardcore.

35:23.538 --> 35:26.165
The more endangered it is,
the more illegal it is,

35:26.249 --> 35:27.833
the more we have to go
to the back rooms.

35:31.046 --> 35:32.046
Go straight up.

35:33.298 --> 35:34.882
So, Louie,

35:34.966 --> 35:36.884
l want to show you
something right here.

35:38.637 --> 35:41.263
You're looking at
a dozen manta rays

35:41.348 --> 35:43.349
sitting right in
these bags right here.

35:44.059 --> 35:46.310
When you consider that each
of these animals

35:46.520 --> 35:48.979
has one pup every couple years,

35:49.231 --> 35:52.817
you're looking at literally
an entire generation wiped out,

35:52.901 --> 35:53.943
just in these bags.

35:57.364 --> 35:59.406
A few years ago, I started
noticing species of

35:59.491 --> 36:02.868
manta and mobula ray
lined up in the streets

36:02.994 --> 36:05.079
in areas that used to be
predominantly shark ports.

36:06.456 --> 36:08.499
And it was really confusing
to me, because I understood

36:08.583 --> 36:10.292
that you can't use their wings
for shark-fin soup,

36:10.460 --> 36:12.920
and the meat from these rays
is very pungent.

36:13.922 --> 36:15.714
It's not worth the time
of bringing in

36:15.799 --> 36:17.424
these huge, heavy animals.

36:19.803 --> 36:21.095
I couldn't believe
when I walked in.

36:21.263 --> 36:23.973
There's just giant, oceanic
mantas all lined up in a row.

36:26.226 --> 36:28.644
And just wanted to know
what was going on,

36:28.728 --> 36:30.938
and then l started watching them
cutting out the gills.

36:31.481 --> 36:33.607
The gills are missing.
Where did they put them?

36:33.692 --> 36:35.067
Where did they take the gills?

36:35.777 --> 36:37.278
And it came down to this.

36:37.571 --> 36:41.782
It was an old cultural remedy
in a very small, coastal town

36:41.867 --> 36:43.784
in southern China,
and that was over 50 years ago.

36:44.411 --> 36:46.954
And that had
largely disappeared,

36:47.122 --> 36:49.540
but I think it was just
following the Sars outbreak,

36:49.958 --> 36:51.250
somebody got it
in their mind that

36:51.334 --> 36:52.543
"Hey, we're running out
of sharks.

36:53.169 --> 36:55.170
"What other products
can we move into the pipeline?"

37:10.061 --> 37:11.896
The gills of manta rays ended up

37:11.980 --> 37:14.315
in all the traditional
Chinese medicine stores

37:14.399 --> 37:15.858
and the dried-seafood stores.

37:43.094 --> 37:46.889
I remember my first encounter
with a manta in the water.

37:46.973 --> 37:48.140
It's something
I'll never forget.

37:50.226 --> 37:52.770
I'm sitting in the water,
and then just out of the blue,

37:52.854 --> 37:56.106
this manta ray does
this huge flyby, right past,

37:57.567 --> 37:59.318
and then goes back
into the blue.

38:00.862 --> 38:03.238
And then I'm just left
breathless, waiting.

38:10.914 --> 38:12.831
Just recently, we were in Bali.

38:14.334 --> 38:16.377
At the end of the last dive,
everyone's out of the water.

38:18.088 --> 38:19.254
And I look down,

38:19.339 --> 38:20.881
and this one manta comes
right underneath me

38:21.883 --> 38:23.300
and then just stops,
and it hovers,

38:23.385 --> 38:25.511
and it's about 1 5 feet down,
and it just-- It's not moving.

38:25.595 --> 38:27.096
And I'm like, "That's interesting."

38:30.475 --> 38:34.395
I look, and there's fishing line
tailing off the top of its body.

38:37.315 --> 38:38.983
And the first thing I did
is I swam down.

38:39.067 --> 38:40.484
I snipped the line off
the top of its head,

38:40.568 --> 38:41.986
right just above the hook.

