And what we don't realize,
it's underneath that,

58:04.106 --> 58:05.940
that's what people
have to worry about.

58:07.067 --> 58:08.943
We do know from
the fossil record

58:09.027 --> 58:12.572
that even pre-human climate
changes could happen fast.

58:13.073 --> 58:14.615
l'm not talking
millions of years.

58:14.700 --> 58:17.451
I'm talking three years
or four years.

58:17.703 --> 58:18.911
Way less than a mortgage,

58:19.413 --> 58:21.247
Less time than it takes for
your kid to go through college.

58:23.083 --> 58:24.250
And what if
the world's temperature

58:24.334 --> 58:26.085
goes up six degrees
in three years?

58:28.088 --> 58:31.090
It will lead to
massive death in the oceans.

58:32.259 --> 58:34.552
When the oceans start dying
like that,

58:35.220 --> 58:37.680
the planet can't function
as it used to function.

58:39.141 --> 58:42.268
And when that happens,
life everywhere fails.

58:45.272 --> 58:46.522
That is a mass extinction.

59:31.485 --> 59:33.694
There's this
remote island in Indonesia.

59:35.364 --> 59:36.364
It's right at the tip,

59:36.448 --> 59:38.783
where the sea comes sort of
crashing into this channel,

59:40.244 --> 59:43.412
and through this quarter
are whales and dolphins

59:43.497 --> 59:44.497
and all kinds of animals.

59:49.002 --> 59:51.420
And at the tip of this island
is this village called Lamakera.

59:54.216 --> 59:58.928
There's no place on Earth that
we know of where more manta rays

59:59.012 --> 01:00:01.013
are being killed than
in that single village.

01:00:06.728 --> 01:00:09.230
We realized if we were gonna
deal with the manta issue,

01:00:09.856 --> 01:00:11.190
we had to go to ground zero.

01:00:14.152 --> 01:00:15.528
These are manta rays.

01:00:16.238 --> 01:00:18.739
They make, like,
sets of 20 or 40,

01:00:18.824 --> 01:00:20.950
and they're about $20 a set,

01:00:21.034 --> 01:00:22.785
and you get a couple of sets
off a manta, maximum.

01:00:23.829 --> 01:00:25.997
And then you get about
$500 to $600 from the gills.

01:00:27.666 --> 01:00:29.458
Those are gills.
You can see the end of it.

01:00:30.627 --> 01:00:34.046
All the cartilage
will be sent to China

01:00:34.131 --> 01:00:39.802
to be crushed down into pills
for glucosamine sulfate

01:00:39.886 --> 01:00:41.137
for the sore joints
and stuff.

01:00:44.474 --> 01:00:47.059
We sat down to meet with the
Kepala Desa, who's the chief.

01:01:23.388 --> 01:01:25.431
Initially, they weren't
very welcoming.

01:01:25.515 --> 01:01:26.515
They didn't want us to stay.

01:01:28.185 --> 01:01:31.187
But ultimately, we managed
to talk our way onto

01:01:31.271 --> 01:01:32.438
one of the fishing vessels.

01:01:40.572 --> 01:01:42.406
Ask them how they caught it.

01:01:51.166 --> 01:01:52.375
See it?

01:01:55.379 --> 01:01:57.046
A couple of hours into
the fishing trip,

01:01:57.130 --> 01:02:01.592
they saw this black figure
on the surface just cruising.

01:02:17.692 --> 01:02:18.943
Paul, left.

01:02:20.445 --> 01:02:22.488
Blood starts to color the water.

01:02:29.663 --> 01:02:30.913
Over the course of an hour,

01:02:31.039 --> 01:02:32.331
this thing struggles
for its life.

01:02:35.585 --> 01:02:36.585
It's big.

01:03:06.116 --> 01:03:07.450
And I'm looking at this,
and I'm going,

01:03:07.534 --> 01:03:09.076
"God, I can't do this."

01:03:11.788 --> 01:03:13.998
He just sticks in the brain
of this animal,

01:03:14.082 --> 01:03:15.833
and it just freaks out.

01:03:21.214 --> 01:03:23.883
And I actually watched its soul
just disappear in front of me,

01:03:25.302 --> 01:03:26.302
and then it went limp.

01:03:36.688 --> 01:03:37.688
Paul, hurry.

01:03:38.899 --> 01:03:40.858
No, no. Don't panic,
don't panic.

01:03:46.364 --> 01:03:47.740
As we're going towards
the village,

01:03:47.824 --> 01:03:49.909
an armada of boats
start streaming past us.

01:03:55.123 --> 01:03:58.083
And they're all triangulating
on this group of manta rays

01:03:58.168 --> 01:03:59.210
that have come into
their waters.

01:04:12.641 --> 01:04:14.808
And the first thing they do
is start hacking into the gills.

01:04:20.649 --> 01:04:24.527
With the advent of traders
providing diesel-powered engines

01:04:24.611 --> 01:04:26.904
and a supply chain
all the way out to China,

01:04:29.115 --> 01:04:32.868
they transitioned very quickly
to a full-on commercial outfit.

01:04:37.374 --> 01:04:38.999
And it's only a few years
before the manta rays

01:04:39.292 --> 01:04:40.334
will be wiped out.

01:04:45.882 --> 01:04:47.675
They realize
the numbers are dropping.

01:04:50.345 --> 01:04:54.306
Even if we weren't here, they
realize something has to change.

01:04:59.104 --> 01:05:00.896
What are their children
going to be doing?

01:05:03.817 --> 01:05:04.900
They're gonna have nothing left.

01:05:14.077 --> 01:05:15.619
It's just losing
a bit of magic, you know?

01:05:15.912 --> 01:05:20.124
The world, without that species,
to me, it's empty, you know?

01:05:40.270 --> 01:05:42.396
In 200 years,

01:05:43.440 --> 01:05:46.692
people will look back
on this particular period

01:05:47.569 --> 01:05:49.737
and say to themselves,

01:05:50.155 --> 01:05:54.116
"How did those people
at that time just allow...

01:05:54.200 --> 01:05:56.619
"...all these amazing creatures
to vanish?"

01:06:03.627 --> 01:06:06.462
But it would be very little use
in me or anybody else

01:06:06.921 --> 01:06:10.507
exerting all this energy
to save the wild places,

01:06:10.634 --> 01:06:13.552
if people are not being educated

01:06:13.637 --> 01:06:16.305
into being better stewards
than we've been.

01:06:26.483 --> 01:06:29.193
If we all lose hope,
there is no hope.

01:06:29.277 --> 01:06:31.779
Without hope,
people fall into apathy.

01:06:35.033 --> 01:06:37.826
There's still a lot left
that's worth fighting for.

01:06:43.792 --> 01:06:44.958
About two decades ago,

01:06:46.503 --> 01:06:49.004
the Baiji dolphin
was extremely vulnerable.

01:06:49.547 --> 01:06:50.756
There was hundreds of them left.

01:06:52.384 --> 01:06:54.802
l mean, I thought, "Well,
there's enough out there.

01:06:54.886 --> 01:06:56.720
"Somebody's gonna do something
to save this animal."

01:06:56.805 --> 01:06:59.348
This animal, it wasn't just
the last of its species,

01:06:59.432 --> 01:07:01.850
it was the last of
an entire family of cetaceans.

01:07:02.060 --> 01:07:04.728
So l thought,
"Humans, somebody, somewhere,

01:07:04.813 --> 01:07:06.188
"has got to go out
and save these animals.

01:07:06.272 --> 01:07:07.564
"They have to,
because they're dying off."

01:07:08.566 --> 01:07:10.693
They're all gone now.
They went extinct.

01:07:11.069 --> 01:07:14.029
ln my lifetime
they went extinct. So...

01:07:21.162 --> 01:07:23.163
We always think that
there's gonna be somebody else

01:07:24.040 --> 01:07:25.791
around to save these animals.

01:07:38.471 --> 01:07:40.973
This field is
one of the last places on Earth

01:07:41.057 --> 01:07:43.058
where you can see
a Florida grasshopper sparrow.

01:07:44.811 --> 01:07:47.104
And there's fewer males
singing every year.

01:07:48.148 --> 01:07:51.525
We're roughly around
20 sparrows a year.

01:07:51.609 --> 01:07:53.193
From 1 50 to 20,

01:07:54.404 --> 01:07:57.197
so it's getting harder every
year to find the bird.

01:07:58.199 --> 01:07:59.241
Did you hear something?

01:07:59.659 --> 01:08:00.784
That's a grasshopper sparrow.

01:08:03.246 --> 01:08:06.540
Phase-out is a term you hear
sometimes by zoo-keepers.

01:08:07.417 --> 01:08:10.419
When a species is
no longer viable in captivity,

01:08:11.379 --> 01:08:12.880
they think about phasing it out.

01:08:14.966 --> 01:08:17.050
Just kind of slip off
into extinction.

01:08:17.676 --> 01:08:18.801
There he is.

01:08:18.886 --> 01:08:20.095
There, you got him, you got him.

01:08:23.640 --> 01:08:24.683
Right there.

01:08:25.518 --> 01:08:27.435
You'll never
phase out an elephant

01:08:27.520 --> 01:08:29.604
or a panda or a rhino.

01:08:31.357 --> 01:08:33.734
But, you know,
if it's a small, brown bird,

01:08:34.903 --> 01:08:37.279
how are you ever gonna get
people excited about that?

01:08:41.868 --> 01:08:45.996
My pictures of the sparrow ended
up on the cover ofAudubon.

01:08:47.540 --> 01:08:50.417
And when the U.S. Fish
& Wildlife Service saw that,

01:08:50.710 --> 01:08:53.337
they went from allocating
$30,000 a year

01:08:53.421 --> 01:08:55.255
towards the grasshopper sparrow...

01:08:55.423 --> 01:08:56.673
Looking good.

01:08:56.758 --> 01:09:02.720
...to about $1 .3 million
this year to try to study it

01:09:03.055 --> 01:09:04.932
and turn things around
for this bird.

01:09:10.438 --> 01:09:11.604
There he goes.

01:09:17.904 --> 01:09:20.363
To me, photography
isn't just about showing

01:09:20.448 --> 01:09:21.740
somebody how beautiful
something is.

01:09:25.662 --> 01:09:26.828
It's a weapon.

01:09:31.376 --> 01:09:33.961
Remember what Ady Gil was able
to do with that little projector

01:09:34.045 --> 01:09:37.256
in front of the Hump?
What he was able to achieve.

01:09:39.716 --> 01:09:43.178
I thought, "Well,
how can we scale this up?"

01:09:48.475 --> 01:09:51.520
When we dream,
we don't dream inside of a box.

01:09:52.229 --> 01:09:53.522
We dream inside of worlds.

01:09:54.941 --> 01:09:56.608
Early photographs were circular.

01:09:57.235 --> 01:09:58.902
Even early TVs were circular.

01:09:59.946 --> 01:10:01.613
But to make more
out of the medium,

01:10:01.823 --> 01:10:04.491
there was a decision made
to crop it into a box.

01:10:06.119 --> 01:10:09.079
And the box has a lot to do with
the way we think.

01:10:11.457 --> 01:10:14.585
My way has always been
blowing up the medium

01:10:14.669 --> 01:10:16.336
into a million pieces...

01:10:16.880 --> 01:10:19.089
...and letting it become
something else.

01:10:28.057 --> 01:10:31.935
Travis has done projections on
iconic buildings all over the world.

01:10:32.562 --> 01:10:34.897
My fantasy would be
to take the work

01:10:34.981 --> 01:10:37.107
of my photographer friends
at National Geographic

01:10:37.191 --> 01:10:40.569
and amplify their message
by orders of magnitude.

01:10:42.739 --> 01:10:45.115
If we would have just
had, like, a whale going by...

01:10:45.241 --> 01:10:46.992
...and then it jumps off
into some other building.

01:10:47.076 --> 01:10:48.160
It'd be beautiful.

01:10:48.578 --> 01:10:51.705
I still love the idea
of sharks on Wall Street.

01:10:52.832 --> 01:10:53.832
What do you think?

01:10:54.042 --> 01:10:56.043
Yeah. No problem.

01:10:57.295 --> 01:10:59.755
80% of the greenhouse gases
that are caused by cities

01:10:59.839 --> 01:11:01.548
are caused
by commercial buildings.

01:11:03.009 --> 01:11:05.177
Tony Malkin, the guy that owns
the Empire State Building,

01:11:05.303 --> 01:11:07.179
probably the most iconic
building in the world,

01:11:07.513 --> 01:11:08.555
and he's greened it.

01:11:09.474 --> 01:11:11.808
Everyone had written off
the Empire State Building

01:11:11.893 --> 01:11:13.435
as outmoded and obsolete.

01:11:13.728 --> 01:11:16.647
We retrofitted
6,500 windows,

01:11:16.898 --> 01:11:18.857
replaced all the lights
with LEDs,

01:11:19.359 --> 01:11:21.318
redid the heating
and cooling systems.

01:11:21.986 --> 01:11:25.906
From that, we actually
saved $4.4 million a year.

01:11:27.283 --> 01:11:28.825
The best way to
move the needle,

01:11:28.910 --> 01:11:30.869
when people are talking
about the environment,

01:11:31.454 --> 01:11:32.746
is the bottom line.

01:11:35.583 --> 01:11:37.209
l like to project
into the woods.

01:11:38.252 --> 01:11:39.711
Try to see
the whole building?

01:11:39.796 --> 01:11:41.004
Yeah, we'd see
the whole building.

01:11:41.089 --> 01:11:42.464
And we could also, like,

01:11:42.548 --> 01:11:44.967
the mobile idea,
where we can mount projectors

01:11:45.051 --> 01:11:47.302
onto trucks
and just drive with them.

01:11:47.387 --> 01:11:48.679
That would be cool.

01:11:49.055 --> 01:11:51.056
Travis had
drawn up an illustration

01:11:51.140 --> 01:11:52.307
of a mobile
projection vehicle.

01:11:52.976 --> 01:11:54.017
Just looking at the plans,

01:11:54.102 --> 01:11:56.144
it opened up a whole new world
of possibility.

01:12:01.025 --> 01:12:03.068
It can't just be
the environmental activists

01:12:03.152 --> 01:12:05.946
that care about
getting off of fossil fuels.

01:12:07.699 --> 01:12:09.241
Everybody has to become
a part of it.

01:12:10.535 --> 01:12:12.285
I heard that
there's this race car driver

01:12:12.370 --> 01:12:14.538
that was an environmentalist
in a sport

01:12:14.622 --> 01:12:16.999
that traditionally doesn't care
about the environment.

01:12:17.375 --> 01:12:19.876
So, like,
a living contradiction.

01:12:20.878 --> 01:12:22.796
When I go to
the sports-marketing companies

01:12:22.880 --> 01:12:24.256
and l say,
"Can you help me find sponsors?"

01:12:24.340 --> 01:12:27.509
And then l give them the list
of people I won't work with--

01:12:27.844 --> 01:12:30.762
No fossil fuels, no oil,
no coal, no meat,

01:12:30.847 --> 01:12:33.849
no people who tested on animals,
no fur, no leather.

01:12:33.933 --> 01:12:35.726
They just look at me like...

01:12:36.644 --> 01:12:38.520
"I don't know how you
want us to help you."

01:12:39.313 --> 01:12:41.982
Leilani MUnter
has just passed five cars

01:12:42.066 --> 01:12:45.318
in the last lap and a half,
and she is real impressive...

01:12:45.528 --> 01:12:47.529
Sometimes,
I have an environmentalist say,

01:12:47.655 --> 01:12:49.531
"Well, if you were really
an environmentalist, you know,

01:12:49.615 --> 01:12:50.615
"you'd be racing a bike."

01:12:50.783 --> 01:12:52.784
And the problem with that
is then I wouldn't have

01:12:52.869 --> 01:12:55.370
75 million people paying
attention to my sport.

01:12:58.458 --> 01:12:59.499
Thank you.

01:13:06.132 --> 01:13:07.716
You look at a guy
like Elon Musk.

01:13:08.301 --> 01:13:11.011
He builds reusable rocket ships
to supply the space station.

01:13:11.929 --> 01:13:14.181
He's the biggest installer
of solar in America,

01:13:14.807 --> 01:13:18.393
and he built the best-rated car
ever made, and it's electric.

01:13:19.854 --> 01:13:21.980
Leilani knew Elon Musk.

01:13:22.065 --> 01:13:26.651
l think we are currently doing
something very, very dumb,

01:13:26.736 --> 01:13:30.739
which is to run this experiment
on how much CO2

01:13:31.115 --> 01:13:32.449
the oceans and atmosphere
can hold.

01:13:32.950 --> 01:13:35.160
In order to have a future
that does not result

01:13:35.244 --> 01:13:37.287
in an environmental catastrophe,

01:13:37.371 --> 01:13:39.039
followed by economic collapse,

01:13:39.415 --> 01:13:42.375
which is what would occur
if we didn't get off oil.

01:13:42.460 --> 01:13:44.336
That's why we have to have
electric cars.

01:13:44.754 --> 01:13:47.089
I think we want to put in
an order for a car today.

01:13:47.173 --> 01:13:48.465
Excellent. Well, take one.

01:13:58.351 --> 01:13:59.559
All right. Go ahead.

01:14:00.103 --> 01:14:01.228
Yeah.

01:14:02.146 --> 01:14:03.438
It's pretty quick.

01:14:03.731 --> 01:14:05.816
Is this gonna go that fast
with 1 05 pounds on it?

01:14:06.025 --> 01:14:07.067
Yeah.

01:14:11.197 --> 01:14:12.280
Oh, yeah.

01:14:12.365 --> 01:14:14.699
You know, I mean,
the focal length on it is crazy,

01:14:14.784 --> 01:14:17.119
but you'll be able to
shoot really far with it.

01:14:17.203 --> 01:14:18.954
You can zoom hundreds
of feet from something

01:14:19.038 --> 01:14:21.623
or like 1 ,000 feet
and scale it.

01:14:21.707 --> 01:14:23.083
Thousands of feet
with this?

01:14:24.168 --> 01:14:25.210
Yeah.

01:14:28.673 --> 01:14:30.006
About how far
will these project?

01:14:30.091 --> 01:14:31.091
A mile.

01:14:31.425 --> 01:14:33.718
Now, I'm building one
for you guys

01:14:34.011 --> 01:14:35.470
that's three times
louder than this.

01:14:40.017 --> 01:14:43.103
Suddenly, there's
just this amazing sound.

01:14:44.522 --> 01:14:45.522
You can't hear that?

01:14:49.986 --> 01:14:53.572
We've taken inspiration from
ocean creatures, like plankton,

01:14:53.656 --> 01:14:56.908
cuttlefish, that use the light
as a communication device

01:14:56.993 --> 01:15:00.787
or a camouflage, and added an
electro-luminescent paint job.

01:15:00.872 --> 01:15:02.122
lncredible.

01:15:02.206 --> 01:15:03.623
With the mobile projection,

01:15:03.708 --> 01:15:05.167
we can go anywhere
we want with it.

01:15:05.251 --> 01:15:08.336
We can take it to the highways.
We can take it to big buildings.

01:15:08.421 --> 01:15:09.838
We can take it to the streets.

01:15:10.256 --> 01:15:12.966
And we'll be able to project
CO2 emissions in real time

01:15:13.301 --> 01:15:15.260
out of the projector
of the back of the vehicle

01:15:15.344 --> 01:15:16.469
while Leilani's driving.

01:15:17.638 --> 01:15:18.763
So, that's legal.

01:15:19.348 --> 01:15:20.473
That's legal?

01:15:20.558 --> 01:15:21.641
Until you push that.

01:15:23.644 --> 01:15:24.978
That works, right?

01:15:25.646 --> 01:15:26.688
That's legal.

01:15:27.190 --> 01:15:28.273
Okay, it's ready to go, boss.

01:15:29.400 --> 01:15:30.609
My feeling is that

01:15:31.027 --> 01:15:33.987
by bringing nature to the city,

01:15:34.614 --> 01:15:36.990
we're hopefully able
to inspire people

01:15:37.783 --> 01:15:39.117
to actually help save
these creatures.

01:15:47.543 --> 01:15:49.878
There's a lot of
species that need protection.

01:15:51.005 --> 01:15:53.423
Most species that are deserving
never get listed.

01:15:56.093 --> 01:15:57.385
After a four-year campaign,

01:15:58.554 --> 01:16:01.556
we finally managed
to get mantas on the docket

01:16:01.641 --> 01:16:04.184
at the 201 3 CITES meeting.

01:16:04.560 --> 01:16:06.311
So, what l want to
show you here is a video

01:16:06.395 --> 01:16:07.562
that shows what we're doing.

01:16:08.648 --> 01:16:10.565
Most people say,
you can't beat money.

01:16:11.150 --> 01:16:12.275
You can't beat politics.

01:16:12.360 --> 01:16:14.653
You can't beat those things
with just hope and inspiration.

01:16:15.154 --> 01:16:17.614
We have to make it
socially unacceptable

01:16:17.698 --> 01:16:18.907
to consume these animals.

01:16:18.991 --> 01:16:20.700
I think we live in
a very visual world.

01:16:21.869 --> 01:16:23.787
Imagery is very powerful.

01:16:25.498 --> 01:16:26.957
'Cause you can walk into a room,

01:16:27.041 --> 01:16:28.750
they might speak
1 5 different languages.

01:16:28.834 --> 01:16:33.088
But you show them a photograph,
people get it. They understand.

01:16:33.172 --> 01:16:34.965
"Supping on
conservation soup."

01:16:35.633 --> 01:16:38.385
There we go.
There's the Hong Kong rooftop.

01:17:05.413 --> 01:17:07.622
Copy that.
Let's just go for it now.

